ΤΗΕ ODES OF HORACE [Boox 11

Evoe! new fears my spirit scare, Yet stormy joy my bosom thrills,

All Bacchic. Spare me, Liber, spare Thy thyrsus and the stroke that kills.

Of founts which milk and wine bedew, Of headstrong Thyads let me tell,

And streams of honey sing anew, From out the hollow trunks that fell.

And next, thy consort's happy star Added to heav’n; and, with the race

Of Pentheus, crushed in deadly war, Lycurgus and his doom in Thrace.

Great rivers and barbaric seas Thou rul'st‚ and, in some hilly spot, The hair of those Bistonides Welldrunk, thou bind'st with snaky knot.

The Giants wound their impious track Athwart the steep of Jove’s domain, But thou strong Rhoetus hurledst back,

With claw and fang os lion slain.

‘More apt for dance and sport and jest, No fighter.' Such was rumour's course. But now thy godhead stands confessed In war as peace a central force.
